WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:07.000
So, inside the render body of order, we want to take care of the checkout at this particular level.

00:11.000 --> 00:13.000
Just to kind of show you how you would do this.

00:18.000 --> 00:21.000
So we're going to write an async function called checkout.

00:31.000 --> 00:33.000
We're going to set loading to true.

00:37.000 --> 00:41.000
Because we don't want people to be able to add and subtract things while we're checking out, right?

00:42.000 --> 00:50.000
And then we're going to say await fetch slash API slash order.

00:53.000 --> 00:55.000
And then we want it to be a post.

00:55.000 --> 01:02.000
So, method, post, headers, we have to tell it it's a JSON request.

01:03.000 --> 01:12.000
So, content type application slash JSON. Cool.

01:14.000 --> 01:22.000
We're going to have a body, which is JSON.stringify our cart.

01:26.000 --> 01:34.000
So, if you're not familiar, this is the same as saying cart colon cart.

01:34.000 --> 01:38.000
The name of the thing is cart and the name of the variable is cart.

01:38.000 --> 01:43.000
But in JavaScript, you can just condense that down if they're the same name and just call it cart like that.

01:43.000 --> 01:48.000
When someone checks out, they probably expect their cart to be emptied, right?

01:49.000 --> 01:52.000
So all you do with that is set cart to be empty array.

01:53.000 --> 01:56.000
And set loading to be false.

01:56.000 --> 02:03.000
By this point, because we're doing an await here, then it's just going to wait for this to finish first.

02:03.000 --> 02:06.000
And then once this is finished, then it'll do these things.

02:06.000 --> 02:08.000
That's the magic of await here.

02:11.000 --> 02:14.000
Okay. Last thing here, we have this function called checkout.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000
We have the ability to call inside of cart, but we have to pass it from parent to child, right?

02:20.000 --> 02:29.000
So, down here on cart, we're just going to say checkout equals, you probably guessed it, checkout.

02:31.000 --> 02:36.000
And now that function is being passed from parent to child via the props, right?

02:36.000 --> 02:42.000
So that checkout function is now this checkout function, which now we can call very easily with the onClick here.

02:42.000 --> 02:45.000
Let's talk a second about props. We haven't really talked too, too much about it.

02:45.000 --> 02:52.000
It used to be kind of confusing the difference between props and state.

02:54.000 --> 03:00.000
I kind of really pull those concepts apart so that hopefully they're not confusing to each other.

03:00.000 --> 03:03.000
Props are things that are passed from parent to child, right?

03:03.000 --> 03:09.000
So in this particular case, you have the cart, and this is getting the actual cart itself is coming from the parent.

03:09.000 --> 03:12.000
And checkout is a function that's coming from the parent.

03:12.000 --> 03:17.000
But it's important to note here, cart is immutable or maybe stated differently,

03:17.000 --> 03:21.000
you cannot change cart because it came from the parent, right?

03:21.000 --> 03:27.000
So I can't say cart equals cart.push lol, right?

03:27.000 --> 03:34.000
This is not going to do anything because the cart of the parent is separated from the cart of the child.

03:34.000 --> 03:38.000
So, in other words, this is what's called one-way data flow,

03:38.000 --> 03:41.000
which is something that some people talk about sometimes with React,

03:41.000 --> 03:47.000
that data only flows down in components and never flows up, right?

03:47.000 --> 03:56.000
So there's no way I can say inside of this cart, like parent.cart.push or anything like that, doesn't exist.

03:56.000 --> 04:00.000
There's no way to do that directly from the child.

04:00.000 --> 04:07.000
The only way that a child component can affect the parent component is through something like this,

04:07.000 --> 04:11.000
where you pass a function down from the parent to the child and say,

04:11.000 --> 04:16.000
hey, child, when you want to affect the parent, call this function.

04:16.000 --> 04:20.000
So maybe stated differently, cart has no concept of its parent.

04:20.000 --> 04:24.000
It could be the top level component. It could not be the top level component.

04:24.000 --> 04:28.000
It could be rendered here. It could be rendered there. It has no concept of where it is.

04:28.000 --> 04:32.000
It doesn't matter, right? It's its own encapsulated component.

04:32.000 --> 04:35.000
This is different versus like the use state, right?

04:35.000 --> 04:39.000
It uses the mutable part of the child that it can modify itself, right?

04:39.000 --> 04:42.000
And a component can only modify its own state.

04:42.000 --> 04:45.000
It can't modify its child state. It can't modify its parent state.

04:45.000 --> 04:48.000
It can only modify its own state.

04:48.000 --> 04:53.000
So in other words, these components are self-encapsulated.

04:53.000 --> 04:58.000
It can be annoying because it makes it verbose to change things at various different levels.

04:58.000 --> 05:01.000
But it means that if I see that there's a problem with cart,

05:01.000 --> 05:07.000
let's say it is showing the wrong word for checkout.

05:07.000 --> 05:13.000
I'm like 99.99% that the problem is going to be inside of cart.

05:13.000 --> 05:16.000
It makes it very obvious of where problems are.

05:16.000 --> 05:22.000
And that's my favorite part about React is it's very debuggable from that perspective, right?

05:22.000 --> 05:27.000
If there's a problem with checkout here, it means it could mean that the props are passed in incorrectly,

05:27.000 --> 05:31.000
in which case I'd have to go up the parent tree to see, like, what are you passing down?

05:31.000 --> 05:35.000
But at that interface level, like, parent passes in this, child takes this,

05:35.000 --> 05:38.000
makes that interface really easy to debug.

05:38.000 --> 05:41.000
Because I can just open my DevTools, it's like, what are your props, right?

05:41.000 --> 05:43.000
What did you get?

05:43.000 --> 05:49.000
And if it's what I expect of what it gets, right, then I know the problem lies within the child.

05:49.000 --> 05:54.000
So let's go fix the problem that we had here.

05:54.000 --> 05:59.000
It is not header. It's headers.

05:59.000 --> 06:01.000
How dare you browse.

06:01.000 --> 06:05.000
So that's in order.jsx. That's the checkout function.

06:05.000 --> 06:10.000
Just make sure you have headers instead of header.

06:10.000 --> 06:20.000
All right. So then we can come back over here and get your Hawaiian pizza, a couple of those.

06:20.000 --> 06:29.000
Barbecue, add to cart, click checkout, and you can see we get a 200 with an order ID.

06:29.000 --> 06:33.000
So just so you know, this actually is being saved in your database, in the little SQLite file.

06:33.000 --> 06:41.000
So you'll be able to view your orders later, and you can just wonder why did you buy so many Napolitana pizzas?

